You’re asking a good question—does the way we scan (lines, stripes, writing direction) change how we think?
Answer: yes, it shapes perception and some habits of attention—but not in the strong “hemisphere/personality” way you’re suggesting.

⸻

📜 Writing direction actually does differ
	•	English → left → right
	•	Arabic / Hebrew → right → left
	•	Japanese → often top → bottom (vertical), also left → right in modern contexts

So your instinct about directionality is correct.

⸻

🧠 What direction does change

1) Attention flow (real effect)

Your brain builds a habit of:
	•	where to start
	•	where to expect continuation

Example:
	•	Left→right readers often imagine time moving →
	•	Right→left readers often imagine it ←

👉 This shows up in:
	•	timelines
	•	graphs
	•	how people “picture” sequences

⸻

2) Perceptual bias

Direction influences:
	•	how you scan images
	•	which side you check first
	•	how you interpret motion

Example:
	•	A scene moving left→right may feel more “natural” to English readers
	•	The opposite can feel more natural in Arabic readers

⸻

3) Hierarchy vs sequence (vertical vs horizontal)
	•	Vertical scripts (Japanese traditional)
→ reinforce top-down hierarchy / stacking
	•	Horizontal scripts (English/Arabic)
→ reinforce linear sequence / progression

👉 This is subtle, but measurable in how people organize information.

⸻

❌ What it does not do (important correction)

1) Not “left brain vs right brain dominance”
	•	That’s an oversimplification
	•	Both hemispheres are always involved

⸻

2) Not “masculine vs feminine cognition”
	•	No scientific basis for that mapping
	•	That’s a metaphor at best, not a mechanism

⸻

3) Not total cognitive rewiring
	•	Language influences thinking (Linguistic Relativity)
	•	But it doesn’t lock people into fundamentally different brains

⸻

🔥 The real invariant you’re circling

Repeated directional patterns train expectation pathways

That’s the same thing you noticed with lines/stripes.

⸻

